text: I do have a pretty interesting background. I'm actually a graduate student at the University of Pennsylvania, but before the whole Ivy League thing, I actually came from a non-target school. It was an interesting path because, well, just to take a step back, before all this, as with most traders, I was infatuated with the market through gambling. So I kind of dabbled in sports gambling a little bit during my high school and early college days with one of my best friends. And funny enough, I think users would actually appreciate this story, but we used to actually, during this time, sports betting in the US was illegal. So we would Western Union money to some guy in Nicaragua. I kid you not, that's a true story. He's going to be listening to this. He's probably laughing at this too. So we actually used to Western Union money to the guy over in Nicaragua. How did you find this guy? He found the man. That wasn't me. He did all the research on this. So pretty much, I had to say, I'm going to go with the guy. I'm going to go with the guy. Stats background, I was in the math Olympiads or whatnot like that, a little bit of a nerd growing up. And I thought you could use applied statistics to actually get an edge, but I was definitely wrong on that. At least I didn't get an edge. Then I was an accounting major at Long Island University. And as an accounting major, obviously you partake in certain things where you're intertwined with the market. And I started to become a little infatuated with it, decided to try to throw my money into trading, lost all my money, lost my friend's money. We lost his mom's money. And I was like, I'm going to go with the guy. And I was like, I'm going to go with the guy. It was definitely an interesting path. But throughout this time, I was paying my tuition to the markets, not to the school. And I actually started to really get good at what I was doing. I got so good to a point, my finance professor was like, you should really think about this as a career. My mind was set on just going and being an accountant at one of the big four firms. And I really became infatuated with the game. I really loved the game. I had a genuine passion for it. And I remember just saying like, geez, you know, I'm coming from a, you know, on target. I don't know if I'll be able to really break in. I didn't have any internship experience or whatnot. But I know the only advantage that I did have was that I had actual trading experience. And I was managing a small account of like $50,000 for like an investment club and a few investors or whatnot. So I actually had experience trading and managing risk. And I thought that could give me a leg up. But unfortunately, it didn't because every recruiter just didn't give me a shot. So it got so bad to a point, I was literally sending out like hundreds of emails. Stuff on LinkedIn every single day to PMs and recruiters. And I specifically remember actually stalking a few PMs. I found out where they were. I would sit outside on the bench. And as they came out, I would realize, I'd look down and be like, oh, that's the guy. That's his LinkedIn photo. I would approach him and try to pitch him as he walked to Grand Central Station. So it was quite an interesting process. But from there, somebody actually gave me a shot. And I ended up working at the prop desk at Chimera Securities. So that was my first real institutional gig trading there. Then from there, I went to the buy side for a very small equity hedge fund. And then after there, I had the chance to actually work with one of the guys that started the CBOE. He's actually the president of the CBOE Market Makers Association. And this is a really smart guy. I'm so glad I had a chance to be a junior under him. I was his only junior. And I would basically drive out to the Hamptons every single day. It was like an hour long drive and go to this guy's house. And he would show me things on how to do it. And I would go to his house and he would show me how he traded vol and how he looked at options and the entire space. So I definitely learned a lot from him. And from there, I actually went to BMO. And at BMO, I spent some time on the exotics desk, so trading derivatives, and then the listed options desk. So it's quite a transition. But I think what makes my experience so special is that I have experience from all different angles of the market. I had a chance to see what it's like to trade as a retail trader and understand putting on risk as a retail trader, then trading on the prop side, and then on the prop side to the buy side, and then from the buy side to the sell side. So understanding where these different market players lie and understanding why they're taking positions, I had the chance to literally sit in all of those seats. So it gives me a better rounded view, better holistic view of the market and why guys do things and why would they do things. So I think that learning curve was great. So I'm happy that I experienced that struggle early off in my career, because it just molded me into the trader that I am now.
